        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>shirts (main garments) [300212499], main garments for the upper body [300209278], main garments [300209263], clothing [300266639], costume (mode of fashion) [300178802], Costume (hierarchy name) [300209261], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Shirts made from brightly colored printed fabric depicting images of the Hawaiian Islands: palm trees, outrigger canoes, fish, flowers, surfing, and hula dancers. Usually sold to, and worn by, tourists. First made in the 1930s from inexpensive fabric imported from Japan, the popularity of the garment peaked during the 1950s.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047114/Brown, Beautiful, Romantic Hawaii, (1994)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hemden van felgekleurde bedrukte stof met afbeeldingen van de Hawaïaanse eilanden: palmbomen, kano's met outriggers, vissen, bloemen, surftaferelen en hoeladansers. Worden doorgaans verkocht aan en gedragen door toeristen. Ze werden voor het eerst in de jaren 30 van de 20ste eeuw gemaakt van goedkope, uit Japan geïmporteerde stoffen en beleefden hun hoogtijdagen in de jaren 50 van de 20ste eeuw.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052403/Van Dale Groot Woordenboek (1998)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hemd aus mit hellen Farben bedrucktem Stoff, der Bilder der Hawaii-Inseln zeigt: Palmen, Auslegerkanus, Fische, Blumen, Surfer und Hula-Tänzerinnen. Wird in der Regel an Touristen verkauft und von diesen getragen. Als ertes in den 1930er Jahren aus billigem Stoff gefertigt, der aus Japan importiert wurde; die Popularität des Kleidungsstücks erreichte in den 1950er Jahren ihren Höhepunkt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>用顏色鮮豔的印花布製成的襯衫，上面的圖案皆描繪夏威夷島，例如棕櫚樹、浮架獨木舟、魚、花卉、衝浪者和草裙舞者。此類服裝主要賣給觀光客，也常由觀光客穿著。最早於1930年代開始利用自日本進口的平價布料製作，至1950年代達到流行巔峰。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
